1. Study Title
================================================================================

Intellectual Property Literacy, Innovation Readiness and Innovation Practice in Syria's Pharmaceutical Sector: A Cross-Sectional Study
================================================================================
2. STUDY OVERVIEW
================================================================================

2.1 Study Objectives
Primary Objective:
To characterize the empirical co-variation among intellectual property (IP)
literacy, innovation attitudes, innovation readiness, and reported innovation
practice within Syria's pharmaceutical sector, and to assess the comparative 
descriptive contribution of readiness-oriented specifications beyond 
knowledge–attitude formulations.

Secondary Objectives:
• To document the descriptive divergence between attitudinal endorsement and 
  reported innovation practice
• To examine whether readiness contributes additional explanatory fit beyond 
  knowledge–attitude specifications
• To assess variation across professional categories

2.2 Study Design
Cross-sectional observational survey conducted from 10 March to 15 April 2026.

2.3 Ethics Approval
Institutional Review Board: Manara University
Approval Number: MU-URO-26-02
Declaration of Helsinki: Followed
Informed Consent: Obtained from all participants

================================================================================
3. POPULATION AND SAMPLING
================================================================================

3.1 Target Population
Pharmaceutical professionals (practicing pharmacists, pharmacy students, 
academics/graduate students) in a transitional economy.

3.2 Sampling Method
Convenience sampling through professional networks, academic institutions, 
and pharmaceutical manufacturing facilities.

3.3 Sample Size
Target: 400 invitations
Achieved: 303 complete responses (75.8% response rate)
Analytical sample: N = 303

3.4 Inclusion Criteria
• Hold or pursuing a pharmacy degree
• Active professional or student status in pharmaceutical sector
• Provided informed consent

3.5 Exclusion Criteria
• Non-pharmacy educational background
• Incomplete survey responses (>50% missing)
• Potential duplicate responses were assessed using survey metadata

================================================================================
4. VARIABLES AND MEASUREMENT
================================================================================

4.1 Primary Variables (Composite Indices)

All variables are operationalized as empirical composite indices for 
comparative descriptive analysis. They are NOT modelled as latent constructs 
or causal mechanisms.

4.1.1 Pharmaceutical IP Literacy Score (PILS)
• Items: 9 binary knowledge items (K2–K10)
• Scoring: 0/1, summed, normalized to 0–100
• Reliability: KR-20 = 0.485 (reported for transparency only; not a validity 
  criterion for formative composite)
• Self-assessment item (Q10): Included as convergent validity indicator, 
  NOT incorporated into PILS scoring

4.1.2 IP Attitude Index (IAI)
• Items: 10 Likert-type items (A1–A10), 1–5 scale
• Reverse coding: A2, A5
• Scoring: Summed, normalized to 0–100
• Reliability: Cronbach's α = 0.481 (reported for transparency only)

4.1.3 Innovation Readiness Score (IRS)
• Items: 4 binary readiness items (R1–R4)
• Scoring: 0/1, summed, normalized to 0–100
• Reliability: Cronbach's α = 0.507 (reported for transparency only)
• Conceptual note: Treated as a Innovation readiness is treated as a proxy indicator of perceived innovation-enabling conditions.

4.1.4 Innovation Practice Index (IPI)
• Items: 3 binary practice items (P1–P3)
• Scoring: 0/1, summed, normalized to 0–100
• Reliability: Cronbach's α = 0.524 (reported for transparency only)

4.2 Diagnostic Gap Indicator
• Definition: IAI − IPI (descriptive arithmetic difference)
• Interpretation: Reported strictly as a descriptive aggregate-level divergence. 
  NOT interpreted as a latent construct, causal discrepancy, or behavioral 
  mismatch mechanism.
• Note: Difference scores are mathematically redundant with components and 
  inflate measurement error (Edwards, 2001)

4.3 Covariates
• Gender (Male/Female/Missing)
• Professional category (Pharmacist/Student/Academic)
• Experience level (<1 year, 1–5 years, 6–10 years, >10 years)

4.4 Measurement Model Philosophy
All indices are formative composite indicators, not reflective latent scales. 
Inter-item homogeneity was neither expected nor required. Traditional internal 
consistency metrics (Cronbach's alpha, KR-20) are NOT appropriate validity 
criteria for formative measurement models and are reported solely for 
transparency and comparability with prior KAP studies (Coltman et al., 2008; 
Hanafiah, 2020).

