5. STATISTICAL ANALYSIS PROCEDURES
================================================================================

5.1 Software and Environment
• Python 3.12
• Libraries: pandas, numpy, scipy, statsmodels
• Reproducibility: All analyses reproducible via fixed environment 
  specification (requirements.txt provided in repository)

5.2 Descriptive Statistics
• Mean, standard deviation, range, skewness, kurtosis for all domain scores
• Frequency distributions for demographic variables
• Item-level descriptive statistics (floor/ceiling effects)

5.3 Correlation Analysis
• Pearson correlation coefficients for all domain pairs
• 95% confidence intervals via Fisher z-transformation with asymptotic 
  approximation (standard method, no bootstrapping)
• Interpretation: Associative patterns, not causal relationships

5.4 Group Comparisons
• One-way ANOVA across professional categories (Pharmacists, Students, Academics)
• Tukey HSD post-hoc tests if ANOVA significant (p < 0.05)
• Effect size: η² (eta-squared) for overall ANOVA; Cohen's d for pairwise 
  post-hoc comparisons only
• Non-parametric alternative: Kruskal-Wallis test (sensitivity analysis)

5.5 Comparative Specification Models

5.5.1 Specification A: Innovation Readiness (IRS) as Outcome
• Predictors: PILS, IAI, Gender, Student, Academic, Experience Level
• Method: OLS with HC3 robust standard errors
• Interpretation: Associative patterns, not causal effects

5.5.2 Specification B: Innovation Practice (IPI) as Outcome
• Predictors: PILS, IAI, IRS, Gender, Student, Academic, Experience Level
• Method: OLS with HC3 robust standard errors
• Interpretation: Associative patterns, not causal effects

5.5.3 Standardized Coefficients and Partial R²
• β* (standardized beta) for predictor importance comparison
• Partial R² for unique variance explained
• Rank based on partial R²

5.6 Nested Model Comparison
• Baseline (K): PILS + IAI + covariates → IPI
• Readiness-expanded (R): PILS + IAI + IRS + covariates → IPI
• Metrics: ΔR², ΔAIC, ΔBIC
• Primary inference: ΔR² p-value from standard nested model F-test; 
  reported alongside ΔR² in Results
• Interpretation: Descriptive model improvement, NOT evidence of theoretical 
  precedence or causal contribution

5.7 Regression Diagnostics
• Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) — multicollinearity assessment
• Shapiro-Wilk test — normality of residuals (expected non-normal for 
  bounded composite scores)
• Breusch-Pagan test — heteroscedasticity
• Durbin-Watson statistic — autocorrelation
• Note: Non-normal residuals do not invalidate OLS with robust SE 
  (Barker & Shaw, 2015)

5.8 Effect Sizes
• Cohen's r for correlations
• η² (eta-squared) for ANOVA overall effects
• Cohen's d for pairwise post-hoc comparisons
• f² for regression models
• 95% confidence intervals for all primary associations

5.9 Post-Hoc Power Policy
• Post-hoc power calculations are NOT reported in primary analyses
• Rationale: Mathematically redundant with p-values and provide no additional 
  information beyond effect sizes and confidence intervals (Hoenig & Heisey, 2001)
• Sensitivity illustration (Figure S2) presented for context only with explicit 
  disclaimer

================================================================================
6. SENSITIVITY ANALYSES
================================================================================

6.1 Robustness Checks
1. Outlier exclusion: Cook's D > 4/n
2. Alternative SE estimators: HC1, HC2, HC4
3. Alternative group coding: Effect coding vs dummy coding
4. Non-parametric alternatives: Spearman rank correlation, Kruskal-Wallis
5. Alternative gap formulations: PILS−IPI, IRS−IPI, IAI−IPI

6.2 Missing Data Handling
• Complete case analysis for regression models
• One participant (0.3%) with missing gender excluded from gender-stratified 
  analyses only; retained in all others

================================================================================
7. INTERPRETATION FRAMEWORK
================================================================================

7.1 Associative Inference Only
All analyses are explicitly framed as comparative assessments of empirical 
patterns. Coefficients represent associative relationships within 
cross-sectional constraints; no causal, mediational, or hierarchical 
interpretation is implied.

7.2 Proxy Indicator Framing
Innovation readiness is treated as a proxy indicator of perceived innovation-enabling conditions, NOT as a validated latent construct, causal mechanism, or 
individual capability.

7.3 Descriptive Model Improvement and Negative Explanatory Closure
ΔR², ΔAIC, and ΔBIC are interpreted strictly as descriptive model improvement 
under the present specification. They do NOT indicate theoretical hierarchy 
or causal priority. The relatively low explained variance (R² ≤ 0.20) 
indicates that the majority of variation in innovation-related behavior 
remains structurally unexplained; individual-level measures capture only a 
limited portion of system-level determinants.

